<br>
Today, the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://quote.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000103&amp;sid=aYFK9zLgRnbo&amp;refer=us">high court decided</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> in a 6-3 decision that consenting adults actually *can* have sex in a manner they so choose in their own homes.  Sodomites rejoice!  This shouldn't really be a surprise, but the 6-3 margin makes me squirm... we were only 2 justices away from having the Texas law banning gay sex upheld.  A quote from the majority decision:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The state cannot demean their existence or control their destiny by making their private sexual conduct a crime.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
On Tuesday, the Supreme Court <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://quote.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000103&amp;sid=aBjXVqMy_bW4&amp;refer=us">upheld</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> a law that forces public libraries to block pornographic sites if they wish to receive federal funding.  I'm sure most of us know that filtering software is less-than-perfect, and many educational sites regarding sexual activity are completely unavailable due to these filters.  Most people who rely on libraries for their internet access are lower income, and generally less educated, so this could really hinder the ability of poor teens to get information on sex that they really need.<br>
<br>
The Supreme Court didn't really want to come down in favor of censorship, and has in effect re-written the law such that adults can request to have the filters temporarily disabled when they use a library terminal.  All this raises the question - is it more trouble than it's worth?  I suspect many libraries will simply choose not to accept this particular funding, but the ruling may create an interesting precedent for future legislation.  Said Renquist, speaking for the majority:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Because public libraries have traditionally excluded pornographic material from their other collections, Congress could reasonably impose a parallel limitation on their Internet assistance programs.  Public libraries' use of Internet filtering software does not violate their patrons' First Amendment rights.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The other big issue the court hit this week was the University of Michigan's affirmative action policy, and in <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3013784.stm">this ruling</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> the Supreme Court solved almost nothing.  Though the court struck down Michigan's undergrad system which granted extra points to minority applicants, it upheld a similar system in place in the University's Law school.  The undergrad policy was deemed to be a &quot;quota&quot; system, but O'Conner said that the Constitution:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>does not prohibit the law school's narrowly tailored use of race in admissions decisions to further a compelling interest in obtaining the educational benefits that flow from a diverse student body.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Busy week, indeed!<br>
<br>
